{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505801","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505801"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:36:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:36:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2488"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2488","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2488"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.42,0.1,0.15,0.22,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2488"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62494"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2488","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2488"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2488"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47941"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"297"},{"type":"tags","id":"414"},{"type":"tags","id":"2888"},{"type":"tags","id":"3840"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2227"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2261"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7652"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18036"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19209"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62494","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/62494"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for her five-yearly cervical screening test. She is sexually active and has had multiple partners in the past 12 months. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her cervical screening results are as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHPV 16 and 18: not detected\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHPV not 16 and 18: detected\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EReflex LBC: HSIL\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe is referred to a gynaecologist who performs colposcopy, biopsy, and a LLETZ procedure. The histology reveals cervical carcinoma (Grade 1 with involvement of the margins). The patient is then referred to a gynaecologic oncologist.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cone biopsy","Radical hysterectomy","Repeat LLETZ procedure","Surveillance and repeat HPV testing in one year","Radiation therapy"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with cervical screening results indicating high-grade squamous intraepithelial lesion (HSIL) and subsequent histology revealing Grade 1 cervical carcinoma with involved margins. In this scenario, the most appropriate next step is a \u003Cstrong\u003Econe biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E. A cone biopsy is a procedure performed when malignancy is suspected clinically or on cervical cytology. It generally removes a larger and deeper area of the cervix than a LLETZ, it helps clinicians assess the true dimensions and extent of the tumour and can actually be curative for early stage cervical carcinoma if cone margins are not involved. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERadical hysterectomy\u003C/strong\u003E may be considered as a treatment option for early-stage cervical cancer, but this would be premature without the additional information provided by a cone biopsy to properly stage the disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Erepeat LLETZ procedure\u003C/strong\u003E would not be appropriate at this stage, as the previous LLETZ has already revealed carcinoma. Further excision without proper staging could potentially compromise future treatment options.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurveillance and repeat HPV testing in one year\u003C/strong\u003E would be inadequate management for a patient with confirmed cervical carcinoma, even if it is Grade 1. This approach would risk disease progression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERadiation therapy\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate without proper staging of the disease through cone biopsy first. It may be part of the definitive treatment plan but should not be initiated at this stage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s worth noting that HPV-based screening, as used in this case, is known to be more efficacious in detecting pre-cancerous cervical changes than cytology alone. The LLETZ procedure was appropriately performed following colposcopy and biopsy when HSIL was detected. However, given the finding of carcinoma, a cone biopsy is now necessary to guide further management decisions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A cone biopsy is required where initial biopsies are suggestive of malignancy.","HPV-based cervical screening is more effective than cytology alone in detecting pre-cancerous cervical changes.","LLETZ procedure is performed following colposcopy and biopsy when HSIL is expected."],"references":["Cohen P, Jhingran A, Oaknin A, Denny L. Cervical cancer. The Lancet. 2019;393(10167):169-182. Available at: https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(18)32470-X/abstract","Wrede, CD, Brand, A, Hammond, I, Cancer Council Australia Cervical Cancer Screening Guidelines Working Party. Clinical question: Colposcopy and treatment. In: National Cervical Screening Program: Guidelines for the management of screen-detected abnormalities, screening in specific populations and investigation of abnormal vaginal bleeding [online]. 2021. Available at: https://wiki.cancer.org.au/australia/Guidelines:Cervical_cancer/Screening."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47941"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2488"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47941","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/47941"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-17T21:52:58+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-17T21:57:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2488"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62494"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/78"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level III","synonyms":null,"description":"Apply, analyze, evaluate, and create (implementing, organizing, and critiquing information)"